{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01RcJuLuX1Q2nxw84x3JDtzf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the content moderation service and determine the minimum test infrastructure level needed to catch real failures.\n\nI need to think about:\n1. What's the real failure boundary for each behavior?\n2. Could a mock miss this failure?\n3. Does it depend on real infrastructure (OS, network, subprocess)?\n4. Does it depend on real LLM non-determinism?\n5. Does it require multiple agentic steps in sequence?\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: Image with explicit content is flagged and held, not published\n\n**Analysis:**\n- The core logic: image → AI vision model → classification result → if flagged, hold; if not, publish\n- Could a pure Unit test catch this? Yes, if you mock the vision model to return \"explicit_content: true\"\n- But wait... the real failure would be if the ACTUAL vision model fails to detect explicit content. That requires calling the real model.\n- Would a mock hide this? YES! If I mock the vision model to always say \"explicit\", I'm not testing whether the real vision model actually detects explicit content correctly.\n- This is **LLM-dependent**. The behavior depends on what the real AI vision model produces.\n- Level: **Agentic** - you need the real vision model to catch if it actually fails to detect explicit content\n\n**Test description:** Call the real vision model API with a test image known to contain explicit content (e.g., test image from model's training data or curated test set), verify it returns explicit classification, and verify the post is held (not published).\n\n**Plan consistent?** Yes - the test requires calling the real model, which is Agentic level.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.05 (mock could pass, missing real model failures)\n- Integration: 0.10 (local wiring, but still mocked)\n- System: 0.10 (might catch infrastructure issues but not real model accuracy)\n\n\n- Agentic: 0.70 (real model call is critical)\n- Workflow: 0.05 (single agentic step, not multi-step)\n\n## Behavior 2: Text post with hate speech is flagged despite obfuscation\n\n**Analysis:**\n- The real failure: the text model fails to detect hate speech when it's obfuscated\n- Could a mock catch this? Only if the mock is trained on all obfuscation techniques, which defeats the purpose of testing\n- The behavior explicitly requires testing against REAL obfuscation patterns\n- This is **LLM-dependent**: real models may fail on obfuscation in ways you can't anticipate\n- Obfuscation is adversarial - you need the actual model to see if it can handle variations that weren't in your mock training data\n\n**Test description:** Submit text posts with known obfuscation techniques (letter substitution, unicode lookalikes, spacing tricks) to the real text classification model, verify each is still flagged as hate speech, verify posts are held for review.\n\n**Plan consistent?** Yes - the test requires the real model to validate it actually catches obfuscated patterns.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.02 (mock can't test obfuscation robustness)\n- Integration: 0.08 (local wiring with mocked model)\n- System: 0.10 (infrastructure, but not model robustness)\n- Agentic: 0.78 (real model's robustness is the critical dependency)\n- Workflow: 0.02 (single step, not multi-step orchestration)\n\nFor the publishing behavior, the core requirement is straightforward: when both image and text checks pass, the post should be published rather than held or dropped. This is deterministic business logic that doesn't depend on real AI models—I can mock both classifiers to return \"safe\" and verify the publish decision executes correctly. The failure modes are clear: either the code fails to publish when it should, publishes to the wrong state, or silently drops the post. Since this is about decision logic and orchestration wiring rather than model robustness, it falls into the unit or integration range.\n\nFor the timing requirement, I need to verify the full pipeline completes within 5 seconds. This involves measuring end-to-end latency from submission through both model calls and the publish decision, which requires integration-level testing with mocked models to keep execution time predictable.\n\nHowever, the real bottleneck is actual model inference—real vision and text model API calls take seconds, and network latency is unpredictable. Mocks can't fully validate this constraint. The test should run against real infrastructure to catch actual inference time and network delays. This pushes it toward **Agentic** level (real LLM inference dominates the latency) or **System** level (real network and database calls), with Agentic being primary since model inference is typically the slowest component. The primary failure mode is slow LLM inference, so I need real models to validate actual latency. Mocking would hide the real bottleneck entirely. System testing with real infrastructure helps, but the critical piece is running actual model inference end-to-end.\n\nFor the test itself, I'd submit a post with image and text through the full pipeline using real vision and text models, measure the complete latency from submission to completion, and verify it stays under 5 seconds across multiple runs to catch variance.\n\nThis confirms Agentic testing is essential—Unit and Integration won't expose real model latency, System testing alone misses the inference component, so Agentic at 0.60 probability is the minimum viable level.\n\nFor the vision model unavailability scenario, the distinction matters: mocking an exception tests retry logic, but the real failure is when the API actually times out or returns a 503. The actual network behavior and real service degradation are what matter here. This could be System or Agentic depending on whether you're testing just the infrastructure response or the full model interaction, though Agentic becomes necessary if the retry timing and real API behavior are critical to validate. staging instance of the model API.\n\nThe key distinction is what constitutes a real failure here. The actual risk is when the vision model API becomes unavailable—the system should queue the post for retry rather than auto-approving it. Testing this requires either hitting a real endpoint that's down or simulating that condition with a test environment. Since the failure mode involves real HTTP behavior and network error handling (not LLM non-determinism), this falls into System level testing. The test would submit a post with an image while the model API is unavailable or returns a 503 error, then verify the post stays in a retry queue and gets reprocessed once the service recovers.\n\nFor probability distribution: Unit testing could mock the retry logic but wouldn't catch actual timeout behavior (0.05). Integration testing with a mocked service failure and local queuing would be closer (0.20). System testing with real HTTP failures and actual retry handling is most appropriate (0.70). Agentic testing doesn't apply since LLM non-determinism isn't the issue (0.02), and this isn't a multi-step workflow (0.03).\n\nBehavior 6 involves a different concern—whether the same image consistently gets the same classification across multiple submissions within a short timeframe. This directly depends on real LLM behavior since outputs are inherently non-deterministic. A mock can't replicate this unless it's designed to return random values, which wouldn't test the actual consistency of real model calls. Testing real consistency requires hitting the actual model multiple times.\n\nHowever, there's a critical design question: does the system implement caching based on image content hashes? If so, repeated submissions of the same image would return cached results, making this an integration test of the caching layer rather than an agentic test. Without caching, consistency would rely on the model itself being deterministic, which is unrealistic. The actual failure scenario—same image submitted three times in 30 seconds producing different classifications—suggests the system should have some mechanism (likely caching or explicit consistency logic) to prevent this. Testing whether that mechanism works requires either integration-level testing of the cache or system-level testing with real submissions. The minimum level to catch the real failure depends on what's actually breaking. If it's a caching mechanism failing to return consistent results, that's an integration test. If the model itself becomes inconsistent on borderline cases, you need the agentic level.\n\nI think this is agentic because the scenario specifically involves a borderline image where the model might be uncertain. Mocking would mask this—you'd control the mock's consistency artificially. Testing against the real model reveals whether it actually stays consistent across multiple calls on ambiguous inputs.\n\nThough if the system has a caching layer that hashes images and stores results, then the failure could be in that local logic, making it integration-level. But given the requirement describes a consistency guarantee \"when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window,\" this sounds like a system-level feature that needs real model behavior to validate properly. also need **Agentic** testing to verify the mechanism actually handles real model behavior.\n\nThe core issue is that LLMs produce non-deterministic outputs—the same image might get different confidence scores or classifications across calls. For borderline cases especially, this variability matters. The system needs a strategy to handle this, whether through caching, voting, or another approach. Integration testing validates the consistency mechanism itself works as designed with controlled inputs. Agentic testing then confirms the mechanism actually solves the problem when facing real model inconsistency.\n\nI'm settling on **Agentic** as primary because catching the real failure—where consistency breaks under actual model non-determinism—requires real model calls. Integration testing is secondary for validating the underlying caching or decision logic.\n\nThe test would submit the same borderline image multiple times in quick succession, verify all decisions match, and confirm the consistency mechanism is functioning. Probability distribution: Agentic at 0.55, Integration at 0.30, with Unit, System, and Workflow each at 0.05.\n\nNow reviewing all six scenarios: explicit content and hate speech detection both need real models for accuracy, safe post publishing tests the decision wiring with mocks, latency requires actual inference time, vision model unavailability tests real HTTP failures, and consistency demands real non-determinism handling. The core question for consistency is whether the actual failure mode—inconsistent classifications on identical inputs—can only be caught with genuine model calls rather than mocked responses. of only Integration testing is that you miss cases where the cache works locally but the real model returns different values, breaking consistency.\n\nThe realistic minimum is Integration testing for the caching logic plus Agentic testing to validate real model behavior. If forced to choose one, Agentic is the answer—that's where the actual failure risk lives with non-deterministic model outputs.\n\nLooking at the definitions: Agentic means the result depends on real LLM non-determinism or actual model calls, while Integration means multiple modules working together with local storage. For this behavior, the core question is whether results depend on real LLM non-determinism. They do—if the same image gets classified differently due to model randomness, that's a genuine failure. Catching this requires Agentic-level testing with real model calls, making that the minimum level needed.\n\nNow I need to structure the findings with behavior IDs, descriptions, minimum levels, justifications, test descriptions, plan consistency flags, and probability distributions across all test levels. For behavior 1 specifically—explicit content flagging—the real failure occurs when the actual vision model fails to detect explicit content, so mocking won't suffice. The test must call the real vision model API with known explicit images, verify the model classifies them correctly, and confirm the post gets held for review rather than published.\n\nFor behavior 2 on hate speech detection with obfuscation, the core vulnerability is the text model's inability to recognize obfuscated hate speech through techniques like letter substitution and unicode lookalikes. This robustness issue can't be tested with mocks since that would require encoding every obfuscation technique into the mock itself. The test needs to submit adversarial text posts using real obfuscation methods to the actual text classification model and verify each one gets flagged correctly.\n\nFor behavior 3 on safe post publication, the failure mode is in the orchestration logic rather than model accuracy. When both content and text checks pass, the post should be published. This can be validated using mocked models that return safe classifications, since the real risk is in how the conditional logic and state transitions work—whether posts actually get published versus held or dropped.\n\nFor behavior 4 on pipeline latency, mocking the models masks the actual performance bottleneck. Real vision and text inference each typically take 1-3 seconds, so the full pipeline including both checks and the publish decision needs to complete within 5 seconds of submission. This is where the agentic-level failure boundary emerges, since you can't catch latency issues without running actual model inference.\n\nThe test submits posts with images and text through the real pipeline, measures wall-clock time from submission to completion, and verifies the latency stays under 5 seconds across multiple runs to catch variance. Real model calls are essential here—mocking them defeats the purpose of validating actual end-to-end performance.\n\nFor behavior 5, when the vision model becomes unavailable, the system should queue image posts for retry instead of auto-approving them. This requires system-level testing because the real failure mode is when the vision service actually goes down, not when you simulate it in a unit test.\n\nThe test needs to make real HTTP calls to the model service (or use a test environment with real HTTP) to observe how the system handles actual service failures like 503 errors or timeouts. With the vision endpoint unreachable, submitting an image post should prevent auto-approval, trigger a retry queue, and attempt to recheck once the service recovers. Mocking the failure misses the actual network timeout behavior and connection handling that matters in production.\n\nFor borderline image consistency, the core issue is that LLM classification itself is non-deterministic—the same image gets classified differently across runs due to model sampling. Mocking deterministic responses masks this real variability. The test must call the actual model multiple times with the same borderline image within 30 seconds and verify all classifications match, confirming the system's consistency mechanism (caching, hashing, or locking) prevents conflicting moderation decisions despite the underlying model's randomness.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13328,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13328},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c3f15ce6-7e68-49a7-9c63-6ad1d2de3eb5","uuid":"e26c5b2f-36f4-4819-8e4b-d6c5abb7b2a5"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01RcJuLuX1Q2nxw84x3JDtzf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at each behavior, I need to identify where the real failure boundary lies—what infrastructure is required to catch an actual production issue.\n\nLet me work through them:\n\n**Behavior 1 (Explicit content flagged)**: The real failure isn't whether the code *intends* to hold flagged posts—it's whether the **actual vision model detects explicit content**. Mocking the model hides this. You need Agentic-level testing (real model calls).\n\n**Behavior 2 (Hate speech despite obfuscation)**: This is a robustness test. The failure is the real model being blind to obfuscation tactics. Mocking the model to always catch hate speech defeats the test. You need Agentic-level (real model against adversarial inputs).\n\n**Behavior 3 (Safe post published)**: This is pure decision logic: if both checks pass, publish. Failures here are in conditional logic or state routing, not model accuracy. You can catch this at Integration level with mocked safe results.\n\n**Behavior 4 (5-second latency)**: A mock gives you sub-second inference. The real SLA is broken by actual model inference time (1-3s per model + network). You need Agentic-level (real model calls to observe actual latency).\n\n**Behavior 5 (Vision model unavailable)**: The real failure is how the system handles actual HTTP failures (503, timeout, socket error). Mocking a \"service unavailable\" exception hides real network behavior. This is System-level (real HTTP to test service unavailability handling).\n\n**Behavior 6 (Borderline consistency)**: Borderline images expose LLM non-determinism—same image may be classified differently on different calls. Mocking deterministically hides this. You need Agentic-level to verify consistency mechanisms survive real model variance."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13328,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13328},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c3f15ce6-7e68-49a7-9c63-6ad1d2de3eb5","uuid":"0caceb50-680c-45a4-ac8c-6d4802f7fcc7"}
